[PLANNOTATOR EXECUTION]
Execute the approved plan at ${planFilePath}. Refresh HEAD and git status first; stop if stale evidence changes the approach. The parent stays read-only in the invoking checkout: it only coordinates, checks evidence, and reviews and verifies worker results; it never writes or edits anything there. It updates plan status only at the approved plan path outside the invoking checkout. Preserve and protect unrelated work, follow repository patterns, keep each diff scoped, and add or update regression tests with behavior. Every implementation writer, including a single worker, must work in its own isolated worktree. Assign each fresh worker bounded, non-overlapping file and test ownership. Split and launch in parallel only genuinely independent, non-overlapping plan items, with one worktree per worker; serialize dependent or overlapping items. Never allow two writers in one worktree. Require every worker to report its worktree, ownership, diff, and check commands and results. After every implementation diff, delegate to one fresh read-only reviewer to critique it; before integration, send required fixes back to the original owning worker in its worktree and iterate review until clean. Once all worker results pass review, hand them to one designated fresh integration worker in its own isolated integration worktree. The integration worker applies and combines reviewed results serially, owns in-scope conflict resolution, and runs and reports combined focused and required wider checks and final combined diff; no other writer uses that worktree. After the integration worker produces or updates the combined diff and runs its checks, delegate to one fresh read-only reviewer to review the combined diff; send findings back to that same integration worker in its isolated integration worktree and repeat until clean. The parent only reviews and verifies that integration result before marking [DONE:n]. If the original owning worker is unavailable, including if its delegation fails, retry or replace that worker serially in a separate isolated worktree; never let the parent take over implementation. Remaining steps:
